# **Evidence-Based Rowing Training Plans and Methodologies**

Rowing training is a blend of **high-volume endurance work and targeted high-intensity sessions**, structured over seasons to peak for races. Both **indoor rowing (ergometer)** and **on-water rowing** follow the same physiological principles, but on-water training adds technical and crew elements. Below, we explore proven training plans (from the Pete Plan to national team programs), the building blocks of a rowing program, and how to tailor training for different goals—from a novice “couch-to-rower” up to an elite 2k racer. We also delve into the science of intensity distribution (polarized vs. threshold training), specific workout types, testing protocols, and special considerations for various athlete populations. All recommendations are grounded in coaching literature and sports science research.

## **Overview of Major Rowing Training Plans**

![Visualization](data:image/png;base64,)

### **Elite Program Approaches (GB, Germany, USA)**

National rowing programs share common fundamentals: very high training volumes, an emphasis on low-intensity mileage, and periodized intensity. For example, **British Rowing** uses a 7-zone training matrix but broadly follows a three-zone model (low, moderate, high) with a heavy bias to low-intensity work. Research shows elite athletes in endurance sports do **pyramidal/polarized training** – typically **80–95% of training in zone 1 (easy),** and only 5–20% combined in threshold and high-intensity zones. In fact, a survey of German, Danish, Dutch, and Norwegian Olympic rowers found **90–96%** of their training time was below the aerobic threshold (zone 1). This huge aerobic base is the foundation: rowing races might last only \~6–7 minutes, but success comes from the capacity to sustain power aerobically. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full)

**British national team coaches** (e.g. Dan Moore) note that GB crews typically do **pyramidal training in winter** (plenty of UT2/UT1 steady state and some threshold work) and shift to a more **polarized model in racing season**, increasing the amount of high-intensity work while cutting back moderate intensity. The total volume stays very high year-round – often 200+ km per week in winter camps – but the intensity distribution is adjusted to peak for summer racing. For instance, the famous New Zealand pair (Hamish Bond and Eric Murray) were found to use slightly different intensity distributions in their training, but both still maintained a large aerobic component. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

In the **United States**, a similar philosophy prevails. Under coaches like Tom Terhaar (US Women’s team), there’s been an “arms race of volume” in the collegiate and national team scene. Top US university crews may log **150–200 km per week** during winter base training, often doing two practices a day heavy with steady-state miles. This mirrors the USRowing approach of building a massive aerobic base, then layering on race-pace pieces closer to competition. The key differences among programs tend to be in how they implement intervals and strength work, but all successful programs are evidence-based: they allocate a majority of time to endurance rowing and carefully control intensity so athletes can handle the volume. [\[sparks.net\]](https://www.sparks.net/blog/what-is-the-rowing-training-volume-of-elite-programs), [\[sparks.net\]](https://www.sparks.net/blog/what-is-the-rowing-training-volume-of-elite-programs) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**On-Water vs. Ergometer:** It’s worth noting that elite training integrates both ergs and boats. In winter, water time may be limited (in cold climates), so athletes do longer ergometer rows and cross-training (running, cycling, skiing) to accumulate volume. As the season progresses, training shifts to more on-water sessions to hone technique and boat-specific skills. On the erg, intensity is precisely measured in pace or watts; on the water, coaches often use heart rate or perceived exertion to ensure the crew is in the right zone, since boat speed is affected by wind, current, and technical efficiency. Despite these differences, the physiological targets (UT2, UT1, AT, etc.) remain consistent between erg and boat. Successful programs balance the two: **ergometers for power and fitness diagnostics**, and **on-water training for skill and specificity**. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

## **Core Components of a Rowing Training Plan**

**Periodization (Phases of Training):** Rowing training is organized in phases across the year to systematically develop the energy systems and achieve peak performance at the right time. A classic periodization model (after Tudor Bompa) breaks the year into: **Preparatory phase** – further split into a General Prep (base endurance, technique, strength foundation) and Specific Prep (race-specific fitness, anaerobic work); a **Competitive phase**, often with a Pre-Competition build-up and then the main racing period; and a **Transition phase** (off-season rest and recovery). In practical terms: [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf), [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf)

*   **Base/General Prep (Off-season):** High volume, low intensity. Rowers log many kilometers at steady paces (UT2, UT1) to build an aerobic base and capillary/mitochondrial density. It’s common to see long continuous rows and cross-training. Basic strength training (anatomical adaptation and hypertrophy) is emphasized early in this phase to prepare muscles, tendons, and ligaments for heavier loads later. This phase can last several months. For example, Olympic champion rowers Olaf Tufte and Rumyana Neykova reported over **1000 hours/year** of training with a strong emphasis on winter base volume. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf), [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/)

*   **Build/Specific Prep (Pre-season):** Intensity increases while volume might still be high but plateaus. Here the training becomes more rowing-specific: incorporating **threshold pieces, power strokes, and intervals** that simulate race demands. For instance, a crew might add weekly  AT (anaerobic threshold) workouts like 2×20’ at \~lactate threshold, or start doing pieces at 2k race rate in segments (e.g. 4×4’ at 2k pace). Maximal strength training peaks in this phase (after a base of hypertrophy, now focusing on low-rep heavy lifts) before converting to power endurance. This phase bridges the gap between pure base fitness and race readiness. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/), [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf)

*   **Peak/Taper (Competition phase):** In the final weeks before a major regatta, training volume is reduced and high-intensity race-pace work is sharpened. The goal is to **taper** – allow full recovery and supercompensation from training. Athletes do short, intense workouts (like 250m sprint pieces, start practices, or 1k at race pace) with ample rest, to stay sharp without accumulating fatigue. Moderate “threshold” training is minimal in this period; research shows that dropping middle-intensity work as racing nears can help avoid excess fatigue while maintaining polarization (more truly easy or truly hard sessions). The taper might last 1–2 weeks for a 2k event. Coaches ensure rowers feel fresh and explosive on race day. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

*   **Transition (Off-season break):** After the racing season, athletes have a transition period of active rest – typically 2 to 4 weeks of greatly reduced training, unstructured activities, or complete rest for recovery. This downtime helps prevent burnout and allows recovery from any accumulated minor injuries. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/)

This cyclic build-up and taper can happen once per year or multiple times if there are several target regattas (e.g. spring and fall peaks). Many club rowers will do a “winter training” phase, peak for a spring 2k race (like nationals), then perhaps have another training cycle for a fall head race (long distance).

**Weekly Training Structure:** Within each phase, the weekly layout of sessions is crucial. A typical week for an intermediate/advanced rower might involve 5–6 days of training and 1 rest day. For example, a high-performance club program could have: 2 days with interval workouts (e.g. **Tuesday**: anaerobic threshold pieces; **Saturday**: 2k race-pace or VO₂max intervals), 3–4 days primarily steady-state endurance (UT2/UT1) rows or cross-training, and 2–3 strength training sessions integrated on appropriate days. Coaches often **sequence hard and easy days**: after a very intense interval day, the next day’s row will be strictly low-intensity to promote recovery. This allows quality effort on the hard days. For instance, Dan Moore suggests planning your weekly intensity like: if doing speed work on Saturday, then Sunday might be a light recovery paddle, Monday steady distance, Tuesday another hard session, etc., ensuring **48+ hours between exhaustive workouts**. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

A **“typical” weekly distribution** for a collegiate or senior club rower during base training might be:

*   **Mon:** AM 16km steady UT2; PM 60’ weight training (strength).
*   **Tue:** AM intervals (e.g. 5×1500m at 5k pace, L2); PM 40’ easy recovery row. [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)
*   **Wed:** Single session medium-length UT1 row (e.g. 12km at steady 20–22 spm).
*   **Thu:** AM 16km UT2; PM weights (strength/power).
*   **Fri:**  (Often lighter) e.g. technical drills and short UT2 row or rest.
*   **Sat:** Hard interval session (e.g. 8×500m all-out, a “speed endurance” session) plus perhaps a short cooldown row. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm), [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm)
*   **Sun:** Long steady distance (e.g. 20km+ row or cross-training bike/run).

This is just an example; plans vary. At the elite level, athletes might train 2–3 times per day on some days (e.g. adding an extra steady erg or second lift). One of Dan Moore’s example schedules shows high-level rowers doing three training sessions on certain days (morning steady row, midday cross-training, afternoon erg), amounting to \~**12–15 sessions per week** for an elite squad. In contrast, a beginner might only train 3–4 days a week. The key is balancing frequency and recovery: **more weekly sessions** can distribute volume well, but only if intensity is monitored so the athlete isn’t overtaxed. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/)

**Progressive Overload:** All training plans incorporate the principle of progressive overload – gradually increasing training stimulus (volume, intensity, or both) to continue making fitness gains. In rowing, overload is often applied by **increasing mileage or duration** in the base phase, and then increasing the **difficulty of interval workouts** in the build phase. For example, a novice might start with 3×10 minutes at steady pace and over weeks build to 3×20 minutes. Or an interval progression:  in one cycle you do 4×1000m at 2k+5″ pace, later you aim for 5×1000m at the same pace, or 4×1000m a bit faster. **The Pete Plan** explicitly uses this idea: it repeats a 3-week cycle of similar workouts, inviting the rower to attempt a slightly better performance each cycle (e.g. average split on 8×500m improving a bit next time). This cyclical progressive model challenges the body to adapt. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm), [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm)

Overload must be balanced with recovery. Typically, a training plan will insert a **lighter week every few weeks** (a “deload” week) to allow consolidation of gains. For instance, one might do 3 weeks of increasing load, then a 4th week with 20–30% reduced volume and intensity. Coaches often use a change in focus (like a technique week or strength-focus week with lower rowing miles) as a de-facto deload. Failing to include recovery weeks can lead to stagnation or overtraining symptoms. By fluctuating training load (“two steps forward, one step back”), the athlete’s fitness ratchets up over time. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/)

**Volume vs. Intensity Balance:** One of the most critical aspects of a training program is how much time is spent at low intensity versus high intensity. As noted, **rowing is an endurance sport with a large aerobic demand**, so training plans heavily weight towards aerobic volume. Too much intensity can lead to quick fatigue or plateau; too little intensity and the athlete won’t reach peak speed. The consensus from evidence and practice is to do **most sessions at low intensity (UT2/UT1 zone)** and a few sessions at high intensity, rather than doing a lot in the middle. Stephen Seiler’s research in multiple sports found that a polarized approach (about 80% easy, 20% hard) tends to outperform a threshold-heavy approach. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

In practice, that means an optimal plan might have **1–2 hard interval days per week** (HIT sessions), and everything else is primarily steady mileage. This doesn’t imply those “easy” miles are trivial – they are often rowed at a strong steady-state pace (UT1) that is “comfortably hard” but below lactate threshold, to accumulate adaptations without requiring extended recovery. For example, British Rowing’s guidelines emphasize that steady-state (“UT2/UT1”) is **not** a lazy paddle; it should be meaningful aerobic work, because the 2k race is \~80% aerobic. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm)

Programs that violate the 80/20 balance often see problems. If an athlete does too many moderate days (the “no man’s land” of not easy enough to recover, not hard enough to maximally stimulate adaptation), they accumulate fatigue without proportional benefit. Symptoms include feeling stale, elevated resting heart rate, poor sleep, and stagnating erg scores – signs of overreaching/overtraining. Coaches prevent this by monitoring training intensity distribution weekly. In summary: **volume is the cake, intensity is the icing.** A large aerobic base enables higher performance when the icing (intervals, sprints) is applied at the right time. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**Structuring Workout Types:** A good plan also **mixes different workout types** each week to train all necessary components (endurance, power, speed, recovery). Details on session types are in a later section, but in brief: a weekly menu will include some long **steady-state rows** (to build endurance), some **threshold or tempo pieces** (to raise lactate threshold), **interval sessions** of varying distances (to improve VO₂ max or speed endurance), possibly some **sprint work** (short bursts or race starts for neural adaptation), and **recovery paddles**. Striking the right balance is key. Many plans use a format like two hard sessions (one longer intervals, one shorter/faster intervals), with all other rows being longer steady rows of different lengths.

**Cross-Training and Supplemental Work:** Rowing is very demanding, and complementary training can enhance performance and reduce injury risk:

*   **Strength Training:** As noted, strength work is typically \~20% of training time in elite programs. Coaches program 2–4 weightlifting sessions per week, periodized through the year. In the winter prep phase, rowers focus on **hypertrophy and maximal strength** (e.g. squats, deadlifts, presses with progressively heavy loads). This builds muscle cross-section and peak force. As racing season nears, strength training shifts to **power maintenance** – lighter loads, explosive moves, keeping the gains without adding fatigue. The benefits of strength training include increased force per stroke (important since water resistance increases with the square of boat speed, any extra force helps overcome drag) and improved injury resilience. However, strength must be balanced with endurance: doing heavy lifting concurrently with lots of endurance can cause interference (endurance training can blunt strength gains). That’s why at least two sessions a week are needed to see strength improvements in a high-mileage program. If a program cannot accommodate that frequency, some coaches might deprioritize weight training in favor of more rowing. There are cases (e.g. the Kiwi Pair) where champions did minimal formal weight training, relying on rowing itself for strength endurance, but that’s an outlier strategy. Most evidence supports including dedicated strength training to maximize performance, as long as it’s done intelligently (e.g. not doing heavy squats right before a hard 2k erg piece). Plans often place lifting on light rowing days or with sufficient recovery windows. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/)

*   **Mobility and Core:** Flexibility, mobility, and core stability work are integrated, often in warm-ups or cool-downs. Rowers typically have brief daily routines for hips, hamstrings, shoulders, and trunk stability, since the rowing stroke involves compression and extension that can strain these areas. While not always written out in the plan, top coaches ensure athletes stay diligent with **stretching, yoga, or physiotherapy exercises** to maintain range of motion and posture.

*   **Cross-Training Endurance:** Many rowing plans include cross-training modes (cycling, running, swimming, cross-country skiing) especially in the base phase. This allows athletes to increase aerobic volume **without excessive rowing-specific fatigue** or injury. For example, a rower might replace one steady-state erg session per week with a 60-minute run or bike. The aerobic benefit carries over, and there’s some evidence that variety can help overall conditioning. However, since VO₂max and endurance gains can be **sport-specific**, pure cross-training cannot entirely substitute for rowing in a program. Rowers still need enough rowing kilometers to develop technique and local muscle endurance in rowing motions. Many national teams do land cross-training in winter (when on-water is limited) and then shift to almost all rowing by summer, using cross-training as supplemental. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/)

*   **Technique Drills:** Particularly for on-water practice, technical drills (like pausing at certain parts of the stroke, cut-the-cake drills, etc.) are woven into steady rows. While not “physiological” training per se, these drills appear in plans as they improve efficiency. Good technique allows a rower to row faster at the same effort, effectively raising the performance ceiling.

In summary, a comprehensive rowing program is **multifaceted**: large volumes of rowing (or related aerobic work), a select number of interval workouts, strength and conditioning sessions, and adequate recovery periods. This structure must then be adjusted to the athlete’s level and goals, as we discuss next.

## **Customizing the Plan for Different Goals and Athletes**

Different types of rowers will emphasize training components differently. Here we outline how training plans are tailored for various performance goals and populations.

### **Training Plans for Specific Goals**

**1. Beginners (“Couch-to-Row” programs):**  New rowers or those using rowing primarily for general fitness need plans that prioritize technique, injury prevention, and habit-building. Early on, **frequency** is more important than intensity – e.g. rowing 3–4 times per week, even if short sessions, to develop consistency. A beginner plan often starts with very manageable workouts: short intervals and rest periods to gradually accustom the body. For example, Concept2’s *From Couch to Consistency* 4-week plan starts with intervals like *1 min row / 1 min rest, 2 min row / 1 min rest...* up to 3 minutes, which total only \~7–8 minutes of work initially. As weeks progress, it introduces slightly longer pieces (e.g. 15-minute continuous row by week 1’s end) and more interval variety. **Technique drills** and lower stroke rates are included to teach proper form. The focus for beginners is building an aerobic base without exhausting them: intensities are mostly easy to moderate, with perhaps one short hard effort per week to keep it fun and to start adapting the cardiovascular system. Cross-training can be added for variety, but since the volumes are low overall, it’s not usually necessary for recovery reasons (though mixing in bodyweight exercises or mobility, as Concept2 suggests, can help overall fitness). A big element is **motivation** – using things like the Concept2 Online Logbook and million-meter challenges to keep newbies engaged. By the end of a 6-week beginner plan, athletes might be rowing 30–40 minutes continuously and have tried an assortment of workouts (intervals, timed pieces, the online “Workouts of the Day,” etc.). This builds confidence and a fitness foundation for more structured training later. [\[concept2.com\]](https://www.concept2.com/training/plans/couch-to-consistency), [\[concept2.com\]](https://www.concept2.com/training/plans/couch-to-consistency) [\[concept2.com\]](https://www.concept2.com/training/plans/couch-to-consistency)

**2. 2k Race Preparation (Intermediate, 2k target 6:30–7:30):** Many rowing plans are designed around the 2,000m race, the standard for rowing competitions. For a club or collegiate rower aiming in the 6:30–7:30 range, the training is more demanding than a beginner’s, but still might be limited by academic/work schedules. A typical intermediate 2k plan runs 12 weeks leading up to a championship. The **base phase** (first \~8 weeks) will involve heavy aerobic training and gradually sharpening intervals. The athlete will do several steady-state rows per week at varying distances (6k, 10k, 15k pieces, etc.), often using pace targets based on their current 2k PR (e.g. row 8k at \~2k+12 seconds split). The Pete Plan is a good template: each week has one “speed” interval session (short intervals like 8×500m) to build anaerobic capacity, one “endurance interval” (long intervals like 4×2000m or 3×(2500m...down to 2000m) for lactate threshold), and around 3 endurance sessions (steady rows of 30–60 minutes) plus a hard distance piece (like a weekly 10k or 30 min piece to test progress). This covers all bases: the speed intervals push the power up, the endurance intervals and hard distance build race tolerance, and the steady mileage raises aerobic capacity (critical since \~80% of energy in a 2k is aerobic). Weekly volume might be on the order of 50–100 km for an intermediate. As the race nears (last 2–3 weeks), the plan would incorporate more race-specific workouts: e.g. 4×500m at target 2k pace with full rest, or full 2k race simulations, while tapering overall volume the final week. **Test pieces** like a 2000m erg test or a 30 min test might be scheduled at regular intervals (maybe a mid-plan 2k test to recalibrate training paces, and a final 2k). An example intermediate plan is the Concept2 2k 12-week plan, which schedules four sessions a week: a mix of interval formats, gradually increasing intensity, culminating in a 2k test. Intermediate rowers also often incorporate **threshold work** (e.g. 2×20’ at anaerobic threshold) to improve the 6k/30min scores that underpin a good 2k. Compared to novices, intermediate 2k training has more **interval volume** (e.g. 5×1500m, 8×500m, etc.) and the intervals are closer to race pace, to specifically train the physiology of a 6–7 minute all-out effort. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm), [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm) [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm) [\[concept2.com\]](https://www.concept2.com/training/plans), [\[concept2.com\]](https://www.concept2.com/training/plans)

**3. Advanced Competitive (Sub-7:00 2k or Elite):** For highly competitive rowers aiming for sub-7:00 (women) or sub-6:00 (men) 2k times, training becomes very intensive and usually high volume. These athletes are often training 6–12 sessions per week. An advanced program might resemble the **Wolverine Plan or a national team regimen**. Key features include: very high aerobic volume (hundreds of kilometers per month) mostly at low intensity, **two or more hard interval sessions weekly**, and often **tiered intensity** (like the WP Level 1–4 structure) to develop different aspects. For instance, the Wolverine Plan for a varsity college woman was \~6–8 sessions/week: about three low-rate Level 4 workouts (e.g. 2×40’ of varied stroke rate sequences at fixed paces) which together equal a lot of meters, one Level 3 continuous row (60+ min steady), one Level 2 longer-interval session (like 4×2000m or 3×3000m at 5k pace) and one Level 1 speed session (like 8×500m or 4×1k at 2k pace or faster). That yields perhaps 8–12 hours of rowing plus ancillary training. Advanced rowers also do **competitive pieces and trials** regularly – e.g. weekly or biweekly erg tests (like 30 min or 6k tests) to gauge fitness, and seat-racing or matrix pieces in crew boats as part of training camps. Plans for this level often have distinct periods: a **high-volume period** (with sessions like 2× UT2 rows a day, and up to 3–4 Level 4 workouts a week as per WP) building an enormous base, then a **race-preparation period** where training “polarizes” – volume stays high but slightly reduced, and high-intensity (Level 1 and race rehearsal pieces) increases in frequency. For example, at a pre-racing training camp, a national squad might do morning and evening steady rows (100+ km/week) plus several speed workouts (practice starts, 500m pieces, even tune-up races) – one plan showed still **80%+ of mileage at low intensity even at camp, but with more total high-intensity minutes** than earlier. Advanced plans also integrate **more sophisticated recovery monitoring** (heart-rate variability, blood lactate tests, etc.) to fine-tune day-to-day training loads. The end result for a sub-7 2k athlete is a highly periodized, often individualized plan that squeezes the last drops of potential – e.g. mixing endurance rows, hard intervals like 4×4min at VO₂ max, power stroke work (low-rate high resistance), and technical rows to ensure no facet is neglected. [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/), [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/)

**4. Marathon/Long-Distance Rowing:** Some rowers train for long erg pieces (10k, half-marathon, marathon) or lengthy head races (\~5k head races or 19 km Boston Marathon on water). The training for these goals tilts even more toward endurance. The primary goal is to **increase the sustainable aerobic power** and muscular endurance for long durations. A marathon plan will feature extra-long workouts: for example, progressively building the weekly long row from 60 minutes up to 2+ hours. Concept2’s *Long Distance Training Workouts* suggest various long session strategies (like multiple pieces totaling 20k+ in a session). Interval training is still included but often at threshold or slightly below, rather than lots of explosive intervals. For instance, a marathon trainee might do workouts such as 3×15’ or 4×10’ at around marathon pace or a bit faster (half-marathon pace) to get used to time at that intensity. The *Interactive Marathon Plan* (on some rowing forums) often prescribes 2 hard distance rows per week (e.g. a 60min piece and a 30min piece) and several long steady rows. Cross-training can help increase volume without overuse – e.g. cyclists often transition well to long rowing pieces because of similar endurance base. One specific test used in long-distance prep is the **30 minute at rate 20** (30’ r20) – a classic gauge of aerobic capacity and efficiency. Athletes track their distance in 30’@20spm over the training cycle; improvements indicate a stronger base (this test is notably used by the British team as well). Marathon plans also emphasize **nutrition and pacing practice**: workouts to dial in how to fuel during a 3+ hour row and to negative-split longer pieces. Strength training still has a role (to protect shoulders/back during long rows and maintain form), but anaerobic sprints are minimal. Near the event, tapering is still important even for endurance events – typically a 1-week taper for a marathon, where volume is cut maybe 30–50% but a few marathon-pace pieces are done to stay accustomed. [\[concept2.nl\]](https://www.concept2.nl/en/indoor-rowers/training/training-plans-and-resources), [\[concept2.nl\]](https://www.concept2.nl/en/indoor-rowers/training/training-plans-and-resources)

**5. Weight Loss and General Fitness:** For those using rowing as a calorie-burning fitness tool, the training plan will focus on **high-calorie expenditure** and gradual improvements in work capacity. This often means slightly shorter sessions but done more frequently and sometimes at a relatively higher intensity (to boost metabolic rate). A sample rowing-for-weight-loss routine might involve interval training like 1 minute on / 1 minute off repeats (which are time-efficient in burning calories via EPOC), mixed with longer steady rows at moderate intensity on other days. One popular approach is **High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT)** on the erg because it can burn a lot of calories in a short time and raise VO₂ max. Sports medicine research (Laursen & Buchheit, 2013) supports using HIIT for improving aerobic fitness – a weight-loss rower might do, say, 8×30’’ sprint / 30’’ rest (a Tabata-style set) once or twice a week, combined with longer, lower-intensity rows (20–40 min steady) a couple other days to increase total energy burn. The **total volume** might be only 3–5 hours a week, but with a good mix of intensities to maximize fat loss while preserving muscle. Strength training is often included as well for weight loss clients (muscle mass helps raise resting metabolism). In rowing terms, that could be bodyweight circuits or a couple weight sessions, or even using the rowing machine for power strokes (low rate, high damper) to build strength endurance. **Variety** is important to prevent boredom for general fitness folks: one day might be a technique-focused row, another day a team relay or intervals for fun, another an easy paddle while watching TV, etc. The Concept2 community and logs provide many diversified workouts (the **WOD** – Workout of the Day – is often used to keep training fresh). The plan is less about periodizing for a peak and more about **gradual progression and adherence**. Still, applying some periodization concepts can help avoid plateaus: for example, every 4th week could be a lighter “recovery” week even for a fitness rower, to ensure the body isn’t overstressed (especially if also dieting). And as fitness improves, what was once a “moderate” row may become an “easy” row — the plan should escalate difficulty (shorten rest, increase distances, or target faster splits) to keep the weight coming off. But overall, the mantra for fitness/weight loss is *consistency* and *enjoyment* — rowing offers a low-impact, full-body workout, and plans in this category aim to exploit that for maximum calorie burn safely. [\[yumpu.com\]](https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/3809126/goods-gadgets-goods-gadgets-concept2/12), [\[yumpu.com\]](https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/3809126/goods-gadgets-goods-gadgets-concept2/12)

### **Adapting to Different Populations**

**Youth/Junior Rowers:** Training programs for juniors (high school age or younger) prioritize skill development, basic aerobic base, and fun to foster long-term improvement. Young athletes often have limited volume tolerance and are still growing, so coaches are careful with overload. For example, a junior boys’ program might train 5 days a week, focusing on technique and aerobic pieces, with very little high-rate anaerobic work except as races approach. Intensity is introduced gradually: plenty of UT2 steady state (which juniors respond well to, building cardiovascular base) and short intervals more as technique exercises than full engine-busters. Because juniors recover quickly, they can handle frequency, but the **overall miles per week** will be lower than for adults. A 15-year-old might row, say, 40–60 km per week, whereas an adult rower might do 100+ km at the same competitive level. Junior plans also integrate more cross-training (many scholastic programs include running or erging only 2–3 times a week and other sports on off days) to develop general athleticism. Strength training for those under \~16 is usually bodyweight or light resistance focusing on core and mobility, until they reach physical maturity to lift heavier safely. Another consideration is **academic scheduling** – school teams often have seasons (fall head race season, spring sprint season) with an off-season in summer. So their periodization might be a half-year cycle rather than a full-year continuous plan. Coaches also ensure variety to keep it fun: relay races on ergs, technique drills in singles, etc., to engage young athletes. The bottom line: junior rowers’ plans emphasize *technique and aerobic foundation over pure power*, recognizing that their physiology (more fast recovery, but less maximal strength than adults) and lifestyle (school) necessitate a different approach. Volume and intensity ramp up as they progress to U19/U23 levels, bridging to adult-type training only when appropriate.

**Collegiate Athletes:** Collegiate rowers often train almost like elites, but within constraints of the academic calendar and NCAA rules. Many collegiate programs (especially in the US) have a **Fall base season** and a **Spring race season**, with summers often left to athletes to train on their own or with clubs. During the school year, top college teams approach 10–14 hours of training per week, carefully arranged around classes. NCAA limits team practice to 20 hours/week in-season, so coaches often schedule double sessions most days (e.g., rowing in morning, land workout in afternoon) to reach that limit. Additionally, there may be “voluntary” captain-led extra sessions (e.g. individual erg pieces) to boost volume beyond official practice. **High volume aerobic training** is a hallmark: in recent years, many college programs have increased steady-state mileage to emulate the U.S. national team’s success with high-volume training. One coach noted “top programs are putting in more miles than ever, investing the bulk of their training time in aerobic conditioning”. It’s not uncommon for championship-caliber college crews to target \~150 km per week in winter training. However, coaches must juggle intensity because college seasons are short. Typically, fall is spent on longer pieces and perhaps head races (5k), so training includes a lot of threshold rows and longer intervals (like 4×2k, 6k pieces). As soon as January hits, 2k preparation becomes paramount for spring racing, so workouts turn to 2k race pace intervals (e.g. 3×(4×500m) or 1500m/1000m/500m pyramids). **Erg tests** are frequent in college – seat allocation and boat line-ups often depend on 2k erg scores, so athletes may do several 2k tests throughout winter/spring. This effectively forces regular high-intensity efforts in training. The risk is overdoing it, so smart programs segment training with recovery cycles and cross-training (many rowing teams do team runs, stadium stairs, or alternate workouts once a week to vary impact). Weight training is standard in collegiate programs as well, usually 2–3 times a week focusing on power and injury prevention. Another aspect is **training camp**: many colleges have a winter training trip where they row twice a day for a week or two, dramatically boosting volume (similar to a national team camp). This can accelerate fitness gains if managed well. In short, collegiate training is about maximizing boat speed in a relatively short timeframe (the athlete’s college career is 4 years) – hence an arms race of maximizing training within limits. This can be tough; as one collegiate rower said, the jump from high school to college training was overwhelming at first. Good college plans ease freshmen in, then ramp them to full load. By senior year, athletes in top college programs are essentially training at a volume and intensity similar to senior national team hopefuls. [\[sparks.net\]](https://www.sparks.net/blog/what-is-the-rowing-training-volume-of-elite-programs), [\[sparks.net\]](https://www.sparks.net/blog/what-is-the-rowing-training-volume-of-elite-programs) [\[sparks.net\]](https://www.sparks.net/blog/what-is-the-rowing-training-volume-of-elite-programs) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/)

**Masters/Older Athletes:** Masters rowers (typically ages 27 and up, but especially those 40–60+) must account for slower recovery and often outside responsibilities (career, family) that limit training time. Masters training plans therefore emphasize **quality over quantity** and smart recovery. Many masters can only train 3–5 days a week, so each session might carry a bit more intensity to still get stimulus. For example, a masters rower with 4 sessions/week might do: 1 intervals, 1 threshold or fartlek, 2 steady endurance rows. Compared to younger athletes, masters need longer warm-ups, more stretching, and often **lower-impact cross-training** to supplement rowing without injury (cycling and swimming are popular for aerobic work). The intensity distribution might shift slightly – some masters effectively do a more **pyramidal or threshold-heavy** approach by necessity, since doing 80% of sessions easy might not sufficiently stimulate adaptation if they only row 3 times a week. Research indicates if you have fewer sessions, you can tolerate making a higher fraction of them intense because you have more recovery time. For instance, a masters rower training Monday/Wednesday/Saturday could conceivably do a hard workout each of those days (with light cross-training Tue/Thu), whereas a younger athlete doing 6 sessions wouldn’t do 3 intense out of 6 routinely. Still, masters must be cautious: the risk of injury or overtraining on limited volume is real if they push too hard every time. Often a good balance is one hard, one moderate, two easy per week for masters. **Periods**: Masters benefit from periodization too (some train for masters nationals 1k races in late summer, so they plan winter base, spring build, etc.), but the peaks may be lower and more about feeling fresh rather than absolute max training load. Strength training is valuable for masters to counteract natural muscle loss with age and support joints. Many masters do weight circuits or light-moderate lifting year-round, with focus on core, back, and mobility. Also, **technique focus** can pay big dividends for older rowers – improving skills can raise boat speed without extra physiological load. Masters plans often include technique drills each session and perhaps coaching in sculling to refine stroke efficiency. A major consideration is to incorporate rest and listen to the body: it’s common for masters to take every third week relatively light, or have microcycles like 2 days on, 1 day off to ensure recovery. All in all, masters training is a balancing act: maintaining enough intensity to race fast, but allowing longer recovery and protecting the body. Many successful masters actually adopt polarized training too – doing their long rows very easy (since pushing medium-hard all the time leaves them exhausted) and then really going for it in short race-pace pieces occasionally. The principle of not letting “medium” efforts dominate is perhaps even more important with age, because of limited recovery capacity. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

**Adaptive/Para-Rowers:** Para-rowing includes athletes with physical or visual impairments (classified as PR1, PR2, PR3 depending on use of legs/trunk/arms). Training methodologies for para athletes follow the same evidence-based principles, but with **adjustments for each athlete’s abilities and recovery needs**. For example, a PR1 (arms and shoulders only) rower will focus almost exclusively on upper-body and core endurance. Their sessions on the erg (or arms-only ergometer) will be shorter in distance for the same effort (since they use less muscle mass, the aerobic strain concentrates quickly). They might do more frequent short sessions rather than few long rows. The GB para-rowing team, for instance, are full-time athletes but “do fewer sessions than their able-bodied teammates” to maximize quality and recovery. This “less is more” approach recognizes that many adaptive athletes cannot tolerate the huge volumes of able-bodied rowers without risk of overuse injury or exhaustion. Instead, they zero in on key workouts – e.g. interval training that improves what muscle groups they can use, technique drills to maximize stroke efficiency, and ample rest. Cross-training is also common: a PR2 athlete (trunk and arms) might use a hand cycle or wheelchair athletics for additional cardio work. **Strength and rehab exercises** are critical parts of para programs, to strengthen supporting muscles and prevent injuries given any asymmetries or prosthetics use. A para rower with a single leg, for instance, will do lots of work to keep the back and hip on the affected side healthy. Periodization still applies – base endurance comes first, then more intensity. However, tapering might be slightly longer if recovery is an issue (ensuring the athlete feels 100% on race day). Coaches also must adapt technique and equipment (e.g. fixed seats, strapping) which can affect training dynamics; for instance, without leg drive, a PR1 rower’s stroke-rate in training might be higher to get equivalent intensity. Paras often incorporate **more core stability** and **balance training** to optimize what they have. Another aspect is mental and logistical: training may include more one-on-one coaching, and plans allow flexibility for medical appointments or extra recovery when needed. Despite these adjustments, para rowers follow the same truth: a large aerobic base (even if built unconventionally) combined with race-pace practice yields the best results. The evidence comes from success stories like Britain's Tom Aggar (PR1 Paralympic champion) who followed a structured programme with hard intervals and endurance rows, just carefully modulated – showing that **principles of overload, specificity, and recovery are universal**, only the volume and modalities differ.
