## **Training Principles and Science**

Why do we structure rowing training this way? The methods used by top coaches are backed by exercise science research on how the body adapts to endurance training. Here we highlight key principles and findings that inform rowing programming:

**Polarized vs. Threshold vs. Pyramidal Training:** These terms describe how training intensity is distributed. In a **polarized** model, the athlete does mostly low-intensity (zone 1), a little high-intensity (zone 3), and minimal middle zone (zone 2). A **threshold** model has a large amount of time in the middle (zone 2, around anaerobic threshold). **Pyramidal** is somewhat in-between: mostly low-intensity, with the remaining time spread more in zone 2 than zone 3 (hence a “pyramid” when charted, with low at the base, moderate in the middle, few high on top). [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

Sports science research, notably by Dr. Stephen Seiler, examined the training logs of many endurance champions and found that most (about 80%) naturally gravitated to polarized or pyramidal distributions, not a threshold-heavy approach. The famous rule of thumb “80/20” (80% easy, 20% hard) comes from these observations. Rowing-specific studies echo this: one study of elite rowers compared 11 weeks of polarized vs pyramidal training and found **no significant difference in 2k performance** – both distributions worked, as long as most training was low-intensity (\~90+% in both cases). However, threshold-heavy programs (where athletes spend a lot of time in the mid-intensity zone) often lead to stagnation or overtraining, with researchers noting “mixed training produces mixed results”. The physiological reasoning is that doing too much in the moderate zone can induce substantial fatigue (glycogen depletion, sympathetic stress) but doesn’t allow the truly high-quality intense stimulus nor the volume of easy work needed for big aerobic gains. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full), [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full) [\[studylib.net\]](https://studylib.net/doc/27210784/9.4-block-periodization-by-vladimir-b.-issurin), [\[studylib.net\]](https://studylib.net/doc/27210784/9.4-block-periodization-by-vladimir-b.-issurin) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

For rowers, this means it’s usually best to train either **below the first lactate threshold** (steady UT2/UT1) or **near/above the second threshold** (hard anaerobic pieces), with relatively less in the grey zone between. As we saw, the GB Rowing Team does exactly that: winters are pyramidal (some threshold in mix but still >80% low) and race season polarized (drop the threshold, more HIT). Both approaches keep low intensity dominant. It’s worth noting rowers traditionally used a 5-zone or 7-zone scheme (UT3/2/1, AT, TR, AN etc.), which often resulted in a pyramidal distribution (lots of UT2, some UT1/AT, few TR/AN). Modern training increasingly embraces the polarized idea by ensuring those UT1/AT times don’t creep too high in volume during competition phase. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

A visual example: A training week might have 10 hours at <2 mmol lactate (LIT), 1 hour at 2–4 mmol (threshold, MIT), and 1 hour at >4 mmol (HIT). That’s roughly 83%/8%/8% (pyramidal). Or if threshold is cut further in taper, maybe 86% LIT, 0% MIT, 14% HIT one week – a polarized split. Both adhere to the principle of a large aerobic base. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**Why so much low-intensity?** Because it develops the aerobic energy system with minimal stress, and endurance performance is primarily about aerobic capacity. Rowers have extremely high VO₂ max values and lactate thresholds as a percent of VO₂ max (often >80% VO₂ max at LT), built by years of volume. Low-intensity training stimulates **peripheral adaptations** like increased mitochondrial count and capillarization in muscles. It also can enhance fat oxidation (helping rowers use fat for fuel at moderate intensities, sparing glycogen). Crucially, LIT has a very low recovery cost – “other than needing food, LIT has very little impact on the autonomic nervous system”, so athletes can do a lot of it daily (even twice a day) without burning out. High training volume at low intensity is strongly correlated with success in endurance sports. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**Why not only low-intensity then?** Because to win races, you also need the ability to produce very high power and to tolerate lactic acid in the final minutes of a 2k. High-intensity intervals (HIT) provide **central adaptations** like increasing stroke volume of the heart (raising VO₂ max) and improving the buffering and tolerance of acidosis. They also recruit fast-twitch fibers and can even increase mitochondrial volume in those fibers. But HIT carries high recovery demands (muscle damage, nervous system fatigue). If one did too much HIT, performance could stagnate – studies show adding extra HIT beyond a point yields no further gains and often signs of overreaching appear. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

Thus, the evidence-based formula is: **plenty of LIT to build capacity + some HIT to build power** = best results. Threshold (MIT) training is still used, but carefully. It can improve the lactate threshold itself (delaying fatigue), but if overused it encroaches on recovery as noted. Many coaches include one threshold session a week in base phase then reduce it. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

**Determining Training Zones from Testing:** Since hitting the right intensities is so important, rowers determine their training zones via testing. Common methods:

*   **2k Test or 2k Pace:** In plans like Pete’s or Wolverine, current 2k race speed is a reference. E.g., Pete Plan defines paces relative to 2k PB: 15k “steady” at \~2k+15″ split, intervals at 2k pace or faster. Wolverine Plan prescribes exact splits for L4 based on 2k erg (e.g. 18 spm at 2k+18, 20 spm at 2k+15, etc.). This anchors training intensity to an actual performance measure. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm) [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

*   **Heart Rate and Lactate Testing:** Many serious programs do lactate step tests – the athlete rows incremental workloads (for instance 4-minute segments at increasing paces) and blood lactate is measured to find **LT1 and LT2** (first and second lactate thresholds). These correspond to zone boundaries. For example, if lactate = 2 mmol at 2:10/500m and 4 mmol at 1:50/500m, those may define UT1 and AT paces. British Rowing uses a 7-zone system defined by %HR reserve and lactate; but they note that practically these map into 3 broader zones (low < LT1, mod \~LT1-LT2, high > LT2). If lactate testing isn’t available, **heart rate + RPE** is used. Athletes might do a 20-minute test to estimate threshold HR, etc. Many find their “UT2” zone by conversational effort or \~65–75% HRmax, UT1 by \~75–85% HRmax, etc., aligning with known physiology benchmarks. HR is imperfect due to drift (and underestimates intensity changes due to lag), but it’s a helpful guide in steady state. The “talk test” and how one feels (RPE) is surprisingly effective too – e.g.,  if you can speak in full sentences, you’re likely in low zone; if you’re in threshold, speech is broken. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full), [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

*   **Performance tests (6k, 30min, etc.):** A 6k erg test is often used to gauge aerobic fitness; improvement in 6k time usually correlates with a higher threshold power. Some coaches use a **Critical Power** concept: using 2k and 6k times to derive training paces for different distances (there are rowing calculators that do this). A 30-minute max distance or 10k time trial can similarly indicate if the aerobic base has improved (more meters in 30’ = better aerobic capacity). Athletes and coaches then adjust training splits. For example, if your 30’@20spm distance increases, you might raise your steady-state split accordingly since you’ve gotten fitter.

*   **Monitoring metrics:** Modern tech like RiggingForce or NK SpeedCoach can measure power on water; some teams now prescribe power or pace targets on water sessions analogous to erg splits to keep training in zone.

In essence, testing provides the **individualized intensities** that make training effective. Two athletes with the same 2k time might have different thresholds; testing finds that, so one isn’t overtraining by rowing too hard in UT1. Good programs test at the start of each phase or every 6–8 weeks and then **update training zones** based on progress.

**Minimum Effective Dose & Diminishing Returns:** There’s a concept of getting the most adaptation from the least necessary stress, to avoid wasted struggle. Early in a training cycle or career, relatively small loads produce big gains (e.g., a novice might improve 2k by 30 seconds with just 3 sessions a week). As one gets fitter, more and more training is needed for smaller gains – the curve of diminishing returns. Coaches try to ensure the athlete is doing enough to improve but not so much that it only yields marginal gains at huge cost. Bompa pointed out that once an athlete’s endurance is highly developed, continuing to increase only volume yields minimal improvement – at that point, other factors (like strength or technique) might need focus for performance to keep improving. For example, an elite rower already doing 200km/week likely won’t get significantly faster by adding 20 more km; instead, focusing on say increasing max strength by 5% might enable more boat speed (because their aerobic capacity is near maxed). [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf), [\[worldrowing.com\]](https://worldrowing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/3Chapter6_English-1.pdf)

In practical terms, coaches often ask: what’s the minimum training that still causes improvement? This is especially important for non-full-time athletes (masters, juniors) – they want the biggest bang for buck. Research suggests even with as few as 3 sessions a week, large gains are possible if correctly structured (e.g., 2 high-intensity, 1 longer endurance). But for elite performance, the “minimum” is very high – near the maximum volume one can tolerate without overtraining. Rowers push that ceiling by periodization and recovery. Over time, the training load may deliberately plateau or reduce in some weeks to allow adaptation to catch up (this is the idea of periodisation cycles and deloads as described).

**Recovery Needs and Overtraining Signs:** Rowing training is exhaustive; monitoring recovery is crucial. Signs of positive adaptation versus negative overload can be subtle. **Indicators of positive adaptation** include: resting heart rate staying stable or dropping slightly, the athlete feeling energetic in hard sessions, and metrics like “heart rate for a given pace” improving (e.g., you can row at 2:00 split with HR 150 now whereas it was 160 a month ago). Also, test improvement obviously indicates things are on track. On the other hand, **signs of overtraining/overreaching** include: persistent fatigue, elevated morning heart rate, inability to hit target splits, prolonged muscle soreness, irritability or poor sleep, and sometimes loss of appetite or frequent minor illness. In rowing specifically, a tell-tale sign is when an athlete’s “easy” pace starts drifting upward in HR or they feel they have to push to hold splits that used to be comfortable – meaning they haven’t recovered from prior load. If an athlete is doing too much threshold work, British Rowing’s Dan Moore notes they often end up doing their easy sessions too hard as well (“typical ‘push through it’ mentality”), resulting in *all* sessions being medium and leaving the athlete fatigued and plateaud. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

To manage recovery, coaches build in rest days (at least one full rest day per week for most, aside from perhaps the highest elite level where active recovery might replace full rest). They also incorporate the lighter periods as mentioned. During heavy training blocks, things like **heart rate variability (HRV)**, mood questionnaires, or simply athlete feedback are used daily. A spike in HRV or a drop in subjective sleep quality could trigger the coach to ease off volume that day. Rowers are also taught the importance of nutrition (carbohydrate intake to refill glycogen) and sleep (many aim for 8–10 hours including naps when training hard). These recovery practices are as much part of the training plan as the workouts.

**Deload Weeks and Tapering:** We touched on these in periodization but to reinforce: a **deload week** every 3–6 weeks helps the body supercompensate. Research by Øystein Sylta and colleagues on well-trained athletes demonstrated that periods of recovery after overload are where the gains manifest, and failing to include them risks stagnation. In rowing, a common approach is 3:1 loading (three weeks build, one week light). During a deload, rowers might reduce total distance, cut out one of the interval sessions, and focus on low-intensity technique rows. For instance, a rower doing 100km in build weeks might do 60km in a deload week, keeping a bit of intensity but much reduced. These weeks are often scheduled around life events (university exam week, holiday break) for efficiency. After the deload, athletes often see a jump in performance – like suddenly pulling faster splits – that indicates successful recovery and adaptation. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/) [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/16/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-overview/)

**Tapering** is a special short-term deload before competition. Classic tapering studies (like Mujika, 2000 on swimmers) found that a 1–2 week taper with \~40–60% volume reduction and maintained intensity leads to optimal performance. Rowers follow suit: volume is dropped significantly in the final 5–10 days, but a few high-intensity, race-specific efforts are kept to maintain fitness and neuromuscular sharpness (e.g., doing 1k at race pace a few days out). Also, more rest (maybe two days off in the last week where normally there would be one). The polarized approach naturally happens in taper – moderate work is ditched, some low work remains for recovery (paddling to stay loose). This ensures fatigue is low and the athletes feel “itching to go” on race day. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

All these scientific insights – base training adaptations, intensity distribution, recovery strategies – collectively inform the construction of rowing programs like the ones we described. It’s truly an evidence-based sport now, blending laboratory findings (e.g., importance of VO₂ max, lactate threshold) with on-water experience (e.g., technique and mental toughness).

***

## **Types of Rowing Workouts (and Their Purpose)**

Rowing training is composed of several fundamental workout types, each targeting a different physiological component. A well-rounded program will incorporate all of these at appropriate times. Here are the main categories:

**Steady-State Endurance (UT2/UT1):** These are continuous long-duration rows at low to moderate intensity – the bread-and-butter of rowing training. **UT2** (sometimes called “steady” or “Conversation pace”) is very comfortable, typically \~65–75% of max heart rate, where breathing is easy and you could row for hours. **UT1** is a bit harder (approximately 75–85% HRmax, or close to the aerobic threshold LT1), where effort is moderate but still primarily aerobic. Steady-state pieces can be measured by time (e.g., 45’ continuous) or distance (12km paddle). Often coaches prescribe them by stroke rate cap as well – e.g., “Row 16km at 18–20 spm, HR not above 150.”

*Purpose:* To build the aerobic base – increasing stroke volume, mitochondrial density, and teaching the body to utilize fat for fuel. Also, to refine technique through repetition without fatigue. Rowers improve efficiency in the water with these miles. It's said that “2k is 80% aerobic and these are the sessions where you build your aerobic base”, highlighting why steady state is crucial. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm)

*Examples:*  `3x20min UT2, 2min rest` – maintaining a consistent easy pace. `60 min continuous UT1` – a long piece where the last 15 min might feel tough but you stay aerobic. On-water, a steady state might be “row UT2 for 12km, rate 18, focus on technique X.”

Many programs differentiate **“steady” vs “battle paddle”** – the former truly easy, the latter a bit more strenuous but still below AT. The Pete Plan calls its long rows “15k steady @ \~2k+15” meaning 15 seconds slower split than 2k pace, which is a firm but not hard intensity (for a 7:00 2k, 2k pace is 1:45, so 2:00 split for steady 15k). Mike Caviston’s Wolverine L3 is similar: prolonged rowing “at a fairly steady pace of moderate intensity” aiming for \~60+ minutes continuous. These workouts are done **very frequently** – daily for elites, and multiple times per week for all levels because they carry low risk and high reward. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm) [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

**Threshold / Lactate Transport Pieces (AT, UT0):** These are longer efforts done around the anaerobic threshold intensity (the point where lactate starts accumulating more rapidly, roughly 4 mmol/L for many). They are often 20 to 40 minutes of continuous rowing or broken into a couple of segments. Heart rate will be around 85–90% of max, and the rower will be breathing hard but in control (a classic “comfortably hard” or 7 out of 10 effort).

*Purpose:* To raise the lactate threshold – improving the speed one can maintain aerobically. Training at threshold can increase mitochondrial efficiency and lactate clearance in muscles. This allows a rower to row faster without hitting the wall, critical for 5k-6k races and to make the last 500m of a 2k more tolerable. It’s also a good way to bridge pure endurance and pure interval training. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

*Examples:* A common one is `2 x 20min @ AT, 4′ rest`. If done on erg, the target might be one’s current 60-minute max pace or slightly faster (some use 6k pace as a proxy). Water example: `3 x 2000m pieces at head race pace, 3′ rests`. These workouts hurt – lactate levels reach 4–6 mmol by the end – but they train the body to buffer and delay fatigue.

Another format is `30min at  rate 20–22, best sustainable effort` – many teams do a monthly 30’ test like this; rowing a hard 30min is de facto threshold training because you try to maximize distance which usually pushes you right to threshold/just above by the end. The Wolverine Plan’s Level 2 workouts (e.g. 4×1500m, 5×1500m, 3×2000m) are essentially threshold sessions – intervals totalling \~6–8k at around 5k race pace with short rests. Caviston says these L2s are “longer intervals… totalling 7.5–8k per session” and he indicates they should be done at a pace producing substantial but tolerable lactate (about 5k pace, which is near threshold intensity for many). [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

Threshold workouts are typically done once a week or once every two weeks in many programs (they are moderately taxing, so including more than \~1 can start to push into that threshold-heavy training we caution against). They are particularly common in the **pre-competitive phase** (leading into head races or early season) to build a high cruising speed.

**VO₂max Intervals (High Intensity Interval Training):** These are shorter intervals aimed at improving maximal aerobic power and oxygen uptake. They’re usually 2–6 minutes in duration with rest intervals about equal to work (or slightly shorter). At this length and intensity, the rower’s heart rate will reach near max by the end of each rep, and breathing is very heavy – this trains the central cardio-pulmonary system to its limit.

*Purpose:* Increase VO₂max (the maximum rate of oxygen the body can use). Intervals in the 3–5 minute range are classic for eliciting VO₂max – the intensity is around 95–100% of the power at VO₂max. For many rowers this corresponds to \~2k race pace or a tad faster. By repeatedly hitting high oxygen demand, the body adapts by increasing stroke volume of the heart and capillary recruitment, etc.. These workouts also improve **anaerobic capacity** to an extent and mental toughness. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

*Examples:* A very common format is `4 x 4min, 4min rest` – often at a hard pace (like 1k race pace or slightly above 2k pace). Another is `6 x 500m, 2:30 rest` (500m is \~1:30–1:45 for many rowers, which is in that VO₂max duration zone). Pete Plan’s “speed intervals” are along these lines: e.g. 8×500m on 3:30 rest is a VO₂max workout (the effort is around 2k-pace or a bit faster, with full recovery to allow repetition). He also has 4×1k on 5′ rest – another brutal VO₂ set where the last reps drive you to maximal oxygen use. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm), [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm)

Wolverine Plan Level 1 intervals are similar: 8×500m, 4×1k, 5×750m, etc., all done at 2k pace or faster with enough rest to maintain intensity. Caviston notes he’s “a big proponent of taking adequate recovery to allow appropriate intensity” for these kinds of intervals, meaning you should rest long enough (often 1:1 or even 1:2 work:rest) to hit the target pace each rep. Indeed, 8×500m workouts typically have 3–4 minutes rest for that reason. [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

A classic training theory is that about **15–20 minutes of total work at VO₂max intensity per session** is optimal. Rowing workouts follow that: 5×4′ = 20′ total, 4×1000m \~ 16′ total, 8×500m \~ 16′ total, etc. These workouts are usually done once a week or once every 1–2 weeks, especially in the 6–8 weeks pre-competition.

**Anaerobic/Sprint Intervals:** Even shorter bursts – 10 seconds to 1 minute – fall in this category. These use predominantly anaerobic energy (phosphagen and glycolytic) and train the muscles to produce power quickly. They also train the body to tolerate high lactate levels and clear them.

*Purpose:* Improve peak power (helpful for start and sprint phases) and anaerobic capacity. They recruit the fast-twitch fibers fully. They also can help increase a rower’s ability to sprint at the end of a race and handle the associated acidosis.

*Examples:* **10s-30s power strokes**: e.g., 1:00 at max effort, 3:00 rest, repeated 6 times – a very high-intensity session (lactate can go >10 mmol). **“Thirty on, thirty off”**: 30s sprint / 30s easy, for a series of reps (some coaches do 2 sets of 10 of these, etc.). Those are akin to a Tabata and cross into anaerobic capacity training.

Another example is the **classic rowing start drill**: from stop, do 6 high strokes, paddle 20s, 6 high strokes, etc., or a “shooting start 1’ piece” where you simulate a race start and then stop. These drills build the specific power and skill for quick high-rate bursts off the line or in moves. By practicing them, when race day comes the athlete can execute a 45 spm start with less shock to the system.

In Pete Plan, the “250m/500m/750m/1000m/750m/500m/250m pyramid” in week 3 is a mix of anaerobic capacities – the shorter pieces (\~<1min) in that set hit sprint capacity, while the longer ones (3–4 min) hit VO₂; it’s a hybrid, often leaving one with very high lactate by the end. Caviston mentioned **4×1k** is among the toughest workouts mentally and physically, so he only schedules it every 3–4 weeks – that is a VO₂/anaerobic combo (each 1k yields high lactate). Pure sprints like 20s on/off similarly are used sparingly due to their strain. [\[machars.net\]](https://www.machars.net/waspeteplan.htm) [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/), [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

Sprinters or 500m racers might do more of these relative to endurance work, but standard 2k training will include at least a small dose of sprint work in the final preparations – often in the form of **race rehearsal** (practicing a fast start and sprint finish).

**Race-Pace Pieces and “Pieces” with Varied Rates:** Rowers often practice chunks of the race itself. These workouts mix endurance and anaerobic aspects with the specific rhythm of competition.

*Purpose:* Mainly to develop **race-specific strategy, pacing, and psychology.** Also physiologically to string together various intensities as in a real race – to practice the transition from start to mid-race and mid-race to sprint. It helps with confidence and fine-tuning race plans (e.g., doing a 1000m piece at target race split to see if it’s sustainable, or doing a simulated 2k under suboptimal conditions to build mental toughness).

*Examples:* **“Pieces”** – e.g., 3× (4min + 3min + 2min + 1min, with minimal paddle between) at decreasing ratings – might simulate a 2k in four segments. Or simply **1250m pieces at race rate**, etc. Many collegiate crews seat-race with side-by-side 1500m or 2000m pieces, which doubles as race-pace training. The British training camp example in Dan Moore’s article had things like “seat racing regatta – lots of side by side sprints – and a 2km race at end of camp” – these are intensive but very specific efforts. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/03/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-6-example-programmes/)

Typically, race-pace pieces come in the last month before racing, and not too frequently – maybe once a week or biweekly – because they’re taxing (almost like doing mini races).

**Recovery Rows:** Often overlooked, these are very light sessions meant to facilitate recovery. A true recovery row is short (20–40 min) and at **extremely easy intensity** – heart rate in the UT3 zone (60% HRmax or so). The idea is to get blood flowing to muscles to help clear metabolites and speed up muscle repair, without adding any significant stress.

*Purpose:* Active recovery – research shows low exercise can stimulate blood flow and mitochondrial activity that enhances recovery compared to complete rest, in many cases. In rowing, paddling slowly also provides an opportunity to do technical drills at low workload. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/), [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

*Examples:* A coach might assign “40 min erg very light (fly and die drill, technique focus), keep HR < 130” on the day after a regatta or erging test. Or in between two high-intensity pieces in a workout, they might have athletes paddle 10 min to recover (for example, after a hard 500m, do 10 min at 2:30 split before the next 500m).

Rowers also use the erg or bike for active recovery if they have two sessions on a day: a hard morning workout followed by an afternoon flush-out of 30 min easy spin or row. Physiologically, this flush can help reduce muscle soreness and stiffness by pumping blood and oxygen without further damage.

Crucially, recovery sessions must be truly easy – a mistake some make is turning recovery paddles into another medium session, which defeats the purpose. As British Rowing coaches put it, doing LSD (long slow distance) too hard means it’s not LSD but something in between, which can cause fatigue without extra benefit. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/)

By carefully combining these workout types, coaches create a holistic stimulus: **long steady rows build the base and aid recovery, threshold workouts push endurance limits up, VO₂max intervals raise the ceiling of aerobic power, and anaerobic sprints sharpen the peak power and speed.** Each type has a specific role, and their proportions shift with the training season.

For instance, in base phase: 70% steady, 15% threshold, 10% VO₂max, 5% strength/sprints (numbers illustrative). Pre-competition phase: maybe 60% steady, 10% threshold, 20% VO₂max, 10% sprint/anaerobic. Competition taper: 85% very light, 15% race-pace sprints. This reflects how emphasis moves from general to specific.

***

## **Testing and Progress Tracking**

Regular testing is integral to evidence-based training – it informs training paces, monitors improvement, and guides adjustments to the program. Rowers commonly undergo several types of tests:

**2k Ergometer Test:** The standard rowing test – 2000m all-out on the erg – is the quintessential measure of rowing fitness. It’s used for selection (erg scores often decide boat seats) and is the most directly relevant performance indicator for sprint racing. Many programs test 2k a few times a year: perhaps mid-winter, end of winter, and pre-championship. Some do monthly or biweekly 2k pieces during the heat of selection. A drop in 2k time (e.g., from 7:10 to 7:00) is clear evidence of improved power/endurance, assuming consistency in conditions. If a rower’s 2k isn’t improving despite training, it prompts the coach to analyze why – perhaps they need more high-intensity work, or more rest, etc. Mike Caviston noted that during his own training, he fine-tuned the Wolverine Plan in the 3-4 years leading up to his world record by tracking his 2k performances and seeing what mix of training yielded improvement. Testing paces also help **set expectations for workouts** (like 2k split is used as a benchmark for interval targets as discussed). [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/), [\[row2k.com\]](https://www.row2k.com/features/391/mike-caviston-training-with-the-wolverine-plan-and-working-with-navy-seals/)

**Longer Erg Tests (5k / 6k / 30min / 60min):** These evaluate aerobic capacity and endurance. A 5k or 6k time trial (approximately 18–24 minutes for most) is often used by national teams (US Rowing and others frequently use 6k erg tests for selection in the winter). A better 6k usually correlates with a better base which correlates with a better 2k, though not perfectly. Many college programs test 6k in the fall and 2k in the spring. The **30-minute test** is popular in Europe; British Rowing historically had athletes do 30′ @ rate 20 and measure distance – considered a pure aerobic score. For instance, if an athlete goes from 8000m to 8200m in 30′@20, it’s a significant aerobic improvement (and often has been used for ranking and selection). Similarly, a 60min test or half-marathon erg (21,097m) could be used for those focusing on long distances. Improvement in these longer tests is a sign of increased stamina and efficiency – often preceding improvements over 2k. If an athlete’s 2k stalls but their 6k and 30’ improve, it might suggest their sprint ability is lagging or they need more power; if 2k improves but 6k doesn’t, they might be gaining anaerobic ability at cost of base.

**Lactate Step Test:** Some high-performance centers use periodic lactate profile tests to objectively track changes in threshold. For example, rowers might do a 5-step test (4 min each at progressively faster paces) and get blood lactate readings after each. From this one can derive their lactate curve and see their LT1 and LT2. Over time, with training, you’d expect **the lactate curve to shift right** – meaning at the same submaximal pace, lactate is lower (indicative of improved aerobic efficiency). Perhaps originally a rower hits 4 mmol at 1:48/500m pace, and after 8 weeks of base training, they don’t hit 4 mmol until 1:45 pace – a clear improvement. This can validate that training is working or identify issues (like if threshold heart rate is dropping, maybe overtired). It also helps fine-tune training zones (if threshold moved, training paces should update). Some teams do this 2–3 times a year.

**Max VO₂ Test:** Less common outside research, but sometimes done with a metabolic cart on a rowing ergometer. It gives VO₂max and other data (like at what power VO₂max was reached). If VO₂max increases from, say, 5.0 L/min to 5.5 L/min after a training block, that’s a direct measure of improved aerobic capacity. However, rowers rely more on performance tests as proxies for VO₂max improvements– because usually if 5k time improves, VO₂max almost certainly has improved too.

**On-Water Trials:** On-water, rowers do distance pieces (like a 2000m or 5000m trial on the river) to measure performance in rowing conditions. These are trickier due to environmental factors, but within the same venue, they show if the boat speed is improving. Pairs matrix trials or seat racing pieces also serve as “tests,” albeit more for selection than training feedback (though they do highlight if a rower’s competitive speed is improving relative to peers).

**Strength Tests:** Some programs test things like 1-rep max squat or power clean, or peak power on a dynamometer or even jump tests. Enhanced strength test results can translate to better on-water power. For instance, an increase in squat max might correlate with improved first half of the drive force. But these links are indirect; strength tests are supplementary.

After tests, *analysis* is key. Coaches and athletes interpret the results to adjust training:

*   If the 2k is lacking speed in the last 500m (splits fly-and-die), maybe more lactate tolerance workouts are needed or better pacing strategies.
*   If the rower has a great 6k but underperforms on 2k (common for some with huge endurance but lacking top-end), the program might add sprint work and weights to boost anaerobic power.
*   If tests indicate stagnation, it can indicate overtraining or a need to change the stimulus. Perhaps add a training camp of high volume if they’ve plateaued on intensity, or vice versa. Or simply a rest (maybe a planned recovery week was not sufficient and the athlete is carrying fatigue).

**Tracking Progress Markers:** Beyond formal test days, coaches track everyday training metrics to ensure progress. Split times in workouts – e.g., if last month you did 4×1000m averaging 1:45 and this month you average 1:43, that’s progress. Heart rate response – if for a given UT2 piece the HR is lower than before, that’s a sign of improved efficiency (or sometimes dehydration, so context matters!).

Another metric is the ratio of performance between pieces: e.g., if an athlete’s 2k is disproportionately better than their 6k, it could mean a strength in anaerobic ability but a weakness in endurance – training might be adjusted to raise the base.

Coaches also look at how athletes feel: an athlete handling higher training loads with less complaint than a year ago shows improved work capacity even if test numbers haven’t yet fully caught up.

**Adjusting Training from Data:** The best programs adapt like a feedback loop. For example, the Norwegian rowing team in the early 2000s famously increased their already high volume by \~10% because testing suggested they could recover and benefit from more LIT (in pursuit of marginal gains once everything else was maxed). Conversely, if resting HR and test times suggest an athlete is overcooked, they might dial down volume or intensity. Olympian Xeno Müller once described using HR and lactate data to ensure he was doing his steady state not too hard – when he eased off to proper UT2, he saw better improvement in his 2k, illustrating how monitoring prevented him from training too hard on easy days.

From a scientific perspective, a 1999 study by Weston et al. showed that too much interval training at VO₂max without enough rest led to performance decrements 8 weeks in. So, if a coach notices test performance dipping after adding a second HIT day, they may revert to one. A 2014 study on a Danish LW rower noted 85% training at low intensity accompanied his best improvements – data like that reinforces to coaches not to let the allure of extra intense training override the proven base training. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/01/30/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-2-training-intensity/) [\[frontiersin.org\]](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2017.00515/full)

**Overtraining prevention:** Some coaches implement *functional overreaching* cycles (planned heavy training to spur gains, followed by recovery). They watch test results closely – if a slight dip in performance is seen during a planned overload, it’s expected, but it should rebound strongly after taper. If it doesn’t, that’s a red flag. Psychological signs (motivation loss, irritability) are also monitored. Today, many teams incorporate sports scientists who track wellness questionnaires and HRV daily; significant negative trends prompt intervention (like easing training or doing blood tests for ferritin, etc., to check for deficiencies that can impede performance).

In summary, *“what gets measured, gets managed”* is a motto in training. By measuring performance regularly through tests, rowers and coaches manage the training process – intensifying when needed, backing off when needed, and making evidence-led tweaks to reach the ultimate goal: peak speed on race day.

***

## **Special Considerations and Final Thoughts**

**On-Water vs. Ergometer Emphasis:** As noted earlier, indoor ergo training and on-water rowing are complementary. One special consideration is how much to erg vs. row on water, especially for club rowers with winter climates. Erg training offers reliable, quantifiable workouts (no weather interference), but too much erg can risk technique issues or overuse (the erg’s fixed-seat can strain the back if overdone). On-water rowing adds technical and team elements that erging lacks. Many top programs shift towards more on-water as races near because boat moving skill becomes paramount. However, some athletes (e.g., those training solo without a team) might do mostly erg year-round and still race well on water with a quick transition. The key is to recognize the **specificity** principle: if your goal is a 2k erg race (like CRASH-B Sprints), you can emphasize erg; if your goal is a boat race, you must spend plenty of time in the boat. But general fitness gained is transferable. For non-elite, a practical mix might be ergs for HIT sessions (e.g., a set of 500m intervals is easier to execute on erg) and on-water for endurance rows and technical work. Keep in mind differences: on water, conditions may make exact pacing impossible, so using RPE/HR for intensity control is wiser. Also, scullers often do more **low-rating work** to focus on boat run (which doubles as strength endurance), whereas on erg that might not be as necessary because the drag is constant. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**Integrating Strength without Compromising Endurance:** Another special consideration is **concurrent training** – balancing heavy endurance training with strength gains. Research in concurrent training shows that a high endurance volume can interfere with strength/power development (chronic AMPK activation can inhibit some pathways for muscle growth). Rowing requires both endurance and strength, so the training must juggle these. The British rowing S\&C coach Sam Boylett-Long advises periodizing strength – doing hypertrophy & max strength in the winter when more training is off-water, then maintaining strength during racing with lower volume of lifting, as women in GB do longer into season to offset strength loss. He also notes you need 2–4 strength sessions/week to see improvement in an endurance program; thus masters or time-limited rowers who only lift once a week shouldn’t expect huge strength gains – they may instead use that session for “robustness” (core, injury prevention) rather than chasing PRs. Coaches should schedule lifting so it doesn’t ruin key rowing workouts: e.g., do heavy squats *after* the day’s rowing, or on a light rowing day. Some do an “upper” lift after a hard row day and a “lower” lift after an easy row day to minimize interference. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/27/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-part-4-strength-training/)

**Limited Training Time (3–4 days/week):** For athletes who cannot train daily, each session has to cover more bases. As previously mentioned, they might approach a more polarized or threshold-heavy weekly mix because volume is inherently limited and they can recover more between sessions. For example, a person rowing only Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday might do: Mon – hard intervals, Wed – threshold or fartlek, Fri – recovery or cross-training, Sat – long row. This way they touch high intensity and endurance each week. On fewer sessions, **intensity control** is still important (the danger is trying to go hard every time since sessions are precious – which can quickly lead to burnout). Coaches sometimes remind limited-schedule athletes that “some is better than none” – e.g., if only 30 minutes available on an off-day, doing a short recovery erg or core workout is beneficial. The concept of **micro-sessions** (like 20min morning erg as bonus) can be introduced to sneak in extra volume for those with busy schedules. [\[plus.briti...rowing.org\]](https://plus.britishrowing.org/2023/02/13/designing-an-elite-rowing-training-programme-3-training-intensity-distribution/)

**High-Volume Training Risks:** At the other extreme, athletes doing very high volumes (10+ sessions, 150+ km/week) must take care to avoid **overuse injuries** (rib stress fractures, lumbar strain, tendinitis). Monitoring technique under fatigue is one aspect – sloppy strokes at end of a 30k row could hurt the ribs/back. Incorporating cross-training (like a weekly swim instead of one of the rows) can reduce repetitive strain on same muscles while still giving endurance load. This is why many rowing coaches have land cross-training even at elite levels; for example, Norwegians notoriously cross-country ski a lot in winter to rack up training hours with less rowing strain. Another trick for high volume is varying boat types – e.g., mixing sculling and sweep to change muscle usage pattern, or changing erg drag factor occasionally.

**Injury and Illness Comebacks:** After time off (due to injury or life), coming back should be gradual. A rule of thumb is to start at \~50% of previous volume and build 10–15% per week, while gauging how the body responds. If a rower had a lumbar disc issue, for instance, the coach may reintroduce rowing with shorter sessions (say 3x20min UT2 in first week back) and more cross-training to avoid aggravation, then slowly increase rowing time. Land-based rehab (physio exercises) might temporarily replace one or two workouts a week. It’s critical not to jump straight into full training after an injury – doing so often causes a re-injury or niggles elsewhere. Rowing Stronger’s Will Ruth suggests a **return-to-rowing protocol** where each stage lasts at least one day: e.g., Day 1: very light erg 10min; Day 2: 3x10min, etc., gradually increasing. Only when each step is pain-free should the athlete progress. Coaches also adjust expectations – an athlete who missed 3 weeks might have lost some fitness; the first tests back may be off their PR. The plan should have a mini re-build and maybe skip an immediate race to focus on full recovery. This ties into **long-term development**: sometimes backing off for healing yields better results a few months later than trying to push through.

**Mental Training and Variation:** While beyond pure physiology, it’s worth noting that mental freshness is critical in such a grueling sport. Good programs incorporate variety in training (different venues, different workouts, crew swaps) to keep athletes engaged. Recovery also includes mental recovery – hence why an easy row might be done in a scenic location, or a workout gamified, to relieve monotony. The “art” of coaching is blending the science with an understanding of the rowers’ mindset, keeping them confident and motivated.

**Concluding Thoughts:** Evidence-based rowing training – characterized by large aerobic volume, judicious use of intensity, periodization, and individualization based on testing – has propelled rowing performances to new heights. World best times keep improving incrementally, which many attribute to these optimized training methods (for example, Kiwi pair Bond/Murray credit much of their speed to their relentless volume training, achieving incredible consistency). Meanwhile, the average collegiate or masters rower today trains more systematically than decades ago, benefiting from knowledge shared by experts like Bompa, Issurin, Caviston, Seiler, etc. The principles outlined – from Pete Plan’s structured rotations to British Rowing’s intensity distribution guidelines – form a robust framework that any serious rower can adapt to their level.

In practice, the successful rower is one who can **train a lot, train smart, and recover well.** They use hard science (like lactate readings or VO₂ data) hand-in-hand with listening to their body. They leverage proven frameworks (Pete Plan for 2k speed, Wolverine Plan for detailed structure, Concept2 plans for general fitness) and tweak them to their context (age, schedule, strengths/weaknesses). The result is a program that is comprehensive and evidence-based: periodized phases, a mixture of distance and interval work, race simulations, strength training, cross-training, and regular tests to ensure it’s delivering progress.

By covering the spectrum from novice to elite, from erg to water, and from science to application, we see that while workouts and volumes differ, the **underlying training concepts remain consistent**. As Mike Caviston said, rowing performance depends on the ability to generate energy and resist fatigue – thus training is about finding the optimal combination of high-intensity intervals and prolonged endurance sessions to achieve both goals. The plans and methods described are all diverse routes to that same summit. A rower or coach armed with this knowledge can confidently design a training program tailored to their needs, knowing it rests on the solid foundation of rowing physiology and coaching experience.
